19:18.491 --> 19:25.865 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
siege and aerial bombing
campaign by Russian
and Syrian warplanes; 35,000
people, including

19:25.898 --> 19:31.037 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the remaining fighters and
civilians, were
evacuated in the last two weeks,
after tense

19:31.070 --> 19:32.772 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
negotiations.

19:32.805 --> 19:37.376 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
They joined hundreds of
thousands already
displaced to other
rebel-controlled areas

19:37.410 --> 19:39.111 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
outside the city.

19:39.145 --> 19:45.618 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A convoy of buses leaving the
shattered city
became a symbol of the rebels'
defeat.

19:45.651 --> 19:51.023 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It was a somber exodus of people
who once
came close to overthrowing
President Bashar

19:51.057 --> 19:54.193 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
al-Assad.

19:54.226 --> 19:59.865 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One of those who held out to the
end was Salah
Ashkar, an activist from Aleppo.

19:59.899 --> 20:04.837 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He spent the final days of the
bombardment
documenting it on social media,
and begging

20:04.870 --> 20:13.279 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the outside world for help.

20:13.312 --> 20:17.783 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He fled to Turkey just days ago,
still haunted
by what he saw in Aleppo.

20:17.817 --> 20:20.719 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SALAH ASHKAR, Activist (through
translator):
Death was following us during
the last days

20:20.753 --> 20:22.521 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
we spent in Aleppo.

20:22.555 --> 20:25.825 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The amount of airstrikes we had
there, I don't
think has been seen anywhere in
the world,

20:25.858 --> 20:28.260 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
or the types of bombs they
dropped on us.

20:28.294 --> 20:31.330 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Russian airplanes were
constantly in the
air, never leaving.

20:31.363 --> 20:34.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: But, he says,
help never came.

20:34.133 --> 20:37.837 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
SALAH ASHKAR (through
translator): The people
of Aleppo lost their faith in
countries that

20:37.870 --> 20:39.772 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
supported the revolution.

20:39.805 --> 20:40.873 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Everyone just watched them
dying.

20:40.906 --> 20:43.576 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They watched Aleppo say goodbye
to its people.

20:43.609 --> 20:48.080 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
No one helped us, without
exception, not America,
not France, not Turkey.

20:48.114 --> 20:49.315 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
They just watched.

20:49.348 --> 20:52.518 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: For Salah, the
revolution is
now over.

20:52.551 --> 20:59.492 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A man wanted by the Syrian
regime, if he returns
to Aleppo, he risks arrest,
torture and execution.

20:59.525 --> 21:03.562 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
SALAH ASHKAR (through
translator): I think
I should search for a safe place
where I can

21:03.596 --> 21:07.099 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
be free, I can live my life and
express my
opinion freely.

21:07.133 --> 21:09.668 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I am searching for a new place
to continue
my studies.

21:09.702 --> 21:12.104 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I cannot go back while Assad is
in power.

21:12.138 --> 21:15.908 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: Neither can
anyone who fought
with the rebels.

21:15.941 --> 21:21.080 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On the outskirts of the Turkish
city of Antakya,
just across the mountains from
Syria, we met

21:21.113 --> 21:25.551 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with these two men hiding in an
apartment
after fleeing across the border
two weeks

21:25.584 --> 21:27.319 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
ago.

21:27.353 --> 21:31.090 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Cousins who fought together in
Aleppo, they
were just teenage boys when they
joined the

21:31.123 --> 21:33.325 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
rebels more than five years ago.

21:33.359 --> 21:36.462 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Now they are broken men.

21:36.495 --> 21:39.064 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There is no room for bravado
here.

21:39.098 --> 21:41.934 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They have lost the will to fight
any longer.

21:41.967 --> 21:45.471 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN (through translator): Always
there were
airstrikes.

21:45.504 --> 21:47.740 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They controlled the whole
situation there.

21:47.773 --> 21:49.842 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There was no point in fighting
against them.

21:49.875 --> 21:51.277 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It is finished.

21:51.310 --> 21:53.979 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I felt like there is no point
staying there.

21:54.013 --> 21:55.748 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We could not fight airstrikes
with rifles.

21:55.781 --> 21:59.752 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: They have little
hope for the
people who fled rebel-held areas
of Aleppo.

21:59.785 --> 22:03.789 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MAN (through translator): They
are homeless,
without a future.

22:03.822 --> 22:05.758 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
If they want to work, they will
be beggars.

22:05.791 --> 22:08.194 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They will live in the street,
and have no
future.

22:08.227 --> 22:10.763 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Some lost their sons, others,
daughters and
wives.

22:10.796 --> 22:12.464 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
For them, there is no meaning to
life.

22:12.498 --> 22:14.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It is better to die.

22:14.233 --> 22:19.438 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: Despite the
dangers, others
are still inside Syria, helping
the people

22:19.471 --> 22:22.041 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
who have run from the
government's advance.

22:22.074 --> 22:27.680 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In an environment too dangerous
for most foreign
aid workers, it is often Syrians
themselves

22:27.713 --> 22:31.850 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
risking their lives to help
their fellow citizens.

22:31.884 --> 22:37.256 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
U.S.-based Mercy Corps provides
food and supplies
to many in rebel-held areas.

22:37.289 --> 22:41.126 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They are only able to do this
with the help
of those who stayed.

22:41.160 --> 22:42.928 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CASEY HARRITY, Mercy Corps: It's
incredibly
risky.

22:42.962 --> 22:46.932 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think it is impossible to
understate the
risks that our Syrian colleagues
and Syrian

22:46.966 --> 22:50.436 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NGOs are taking to make sure
that people have
the services that they need.

22:50.469 --> 22:55.007 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They are on the front lines of a
conflict
that has not abated and they are
risking their

22:55.040 --> 22:58.777 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
lives every day to make sure
that these services
reach the people that need them.

22:58.811 --> 23:04.550 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: Back at the
hospital in Turkey,
Mehmet Alver, a pharmacist
living nearby,

23:04.583 --> 23:06.986 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
helps those who come for
treatment.

23:07.019 --> 23:11.557 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He has been overwhelmed by the
huge numbers
running away from the
bombardment in Aleppo.

23:11.590 --> 23:14.360 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
MEHMET ALVER, Pharmacist
(through translator):
I am a human being.

23:14.393 --> 23:15.427 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I have children.

23:15.461 --> 23:16.528 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I have a heart.

23:16.562 --> 23:17.896 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Look at the situation there.

23:17.930 --> 23:20.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I cannot stay in my house just
watching.

23:20.299 --> 23:21.967 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I cannot do that.

23:22.001 --> 23:27.106 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This war happening next to me, I
cannot close
my eyes or close my ears or keep
silent.

23:27.139 --> 23:29.475 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Tomorrow or in the future, that
might happen
to me.

23:29.508 --> 23:34.880 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JANE FERGUSON: After being
bandaged and stitched
back together, these people
can't stay here,

23:34.914 --> 23:37.483 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and must now return to Syria.

23:37.516 --> 23:41.186 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Most of them will have to stay
in refugee
camps, now that they have lost
their homes

23:41.220 --> 23:42.588 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in Aleppo city.

23:42.621 --> 23:52.031 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," I'm Jane
Ferguson
on the Turkey-Syria border.

23:52.064 --> 23:58.304 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Stay with us.

23:58.337 --> 24:03.942 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Coming up on the "NewsHour": a
Greek scientist
who claims he can transform
water to energy;

24:03.976 --> 24:06.645 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and the best of 2016, starting
with books.

24:06.679 --> 24:13.485 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But first: The number of deaths
from opioid
abuse continues to climb,
topping 33,000 in

24:13.519 --> 24:15.321 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
2015, according to the federal
government.

24:15.354 --> 24:20.159 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of the hardest-hit states is
West Virginia,
where the impact of the opioid
problem can

24:20.192 --> 24:22.294 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
reach elementary schools.

24:22.328 --> 24:24.763 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's not the students who are
using, but their
parents.

24:24.797 --> 24:30.035 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Grandparents, foster parents and
the schools
are figuring out how to cope for
the youngest

24:30.069 --> 24:31.704 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
kids.

24:31.737 --> 24:34.440 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Special correspondent Lisa Stark
with our
partner Education Week traveled
to Jackson

24:34.473 --> 24:35.941 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
County, West Virginia.

24:35.974 --> 24:39.278 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's the focus of our weekly
education series,
Making the Grade.

24:39.311 --> 24:43.382 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
A warning to our viewers: Some
of the scenes
may be difficult to watch.

24:43.415 --> 24:51.290 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA STARK: Emily Durst's
fourth-grade class
is a lively place.

24:51.323 --> 24:59.231 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Cottageville Elementary
School teacher
likes to combine math with
movement and with

24:59.264 --> 25:01.066 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
music.

25:01.100 --> 25:07.940 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, it's not surprising that
10-year-old Briana
(ph) Sotomayor looks forward to
school and

25:07.973 --> 25:08.941 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to learning.

25:08.974 --> 25:10.409 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BRIANA SOTOMAYOR, Student: I
love to write.

25:10.442 --> 25:12.511 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I write stories all the time.

25:12.544 --> 25:16.849 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA STARK: Briana came to
Cottageville Elementary
at the end of second grade.

25:16.882 --> 25:19.218 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It had been a tough year.

25:19.251 --> 25:24.690 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
She and her sister Riley (ph)
ricocheted among
four schools and three foster
homes, ending

25:24.723 --> 25:26.492 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
up at the Sotomayor home.

25:26.525 --> 25:30.028 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CARRIE SOTOMAYOR, Mother: They
had reached
a certain point where it was
just they didn't

25:30.062 --> 25:31.163 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
trust anybody.

25:31.196 --> 25:32.931 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They didn't believe anybody.

25:32.965 --> 25:39.371 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: For the sisters,
life had had
a rough start, born to a mother
addicted to

25:39.405 --> 25:44.076 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
drugs, including prescription
pain pills,
and a father in and out of jail.

25:44.109 --> 25:53.852 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CARRIE SOTOMAYOR: They were able
to in great
detail tell you how to crush
pain medications

25:53.886 --> 25:59.691 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and mix them with water and
inject them, among
other things.

25:59.725 --> 26:02.561 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, they knew far more about it
than I did.

26:02.594 --> 26:08.867 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: Carrie and Paul
Sotomayor have
now adopted the girls, and also
a little boy,

26:08.901 --> 26:12.237 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Zeke (ph), who had been
neglected as an infant.

26:12.271 --> 26:13.972 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Now they're a family.

26:14.006 --> 26:17.409 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
PAUL SOTOMAYOR, Father: We have
adopted three
children, and, lord willing, one
more.

26:17.443 --> 26:22.748 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: Like Briana and
Riley, the fourth
child they hope to adopt, a boy,
3 months

26:22.781 --> 26:26.318 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
old, was also born to a
drug-addicted mother.

26:26.351 --> 26:31.690 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CARRIE SOTOMAYOR: When we
brought him through
the door, Riley just burst into
tears and

26:31.723 --> 26:36.395 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
said, how could anybody have
done drugs and
hurt this little baby?

26:36.428 --> 26:38.764 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And it just -- it broke her
heart.

26:38.797 --> 26:44.436 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: The impact of the
opioid epidemic
on children, parents almost
dying from pain

26:44.470 --> 26:53.045 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
pills, fentanyl or heroin, has
been on graphic
display in pictures released by
law enforcement.

26:53.078 --> 26:55.981 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The epidemic has hit hard in
West Virginia.

26:56.014 --> 27:01.053 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
With more parents abusing drugs,
the number
of children placed in foster
care has jumped

27:01.086 --> 27:06.692 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
24 percent in five years, to
more than 5,000.

27:06.725 --> 27:12.164 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Here in Jackson County, local
officials saw
a spike in overdoses among
adults after this

27:12.197 --> 27:17.069 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
aluminum factory shut down in
2009, throwing
hundreds out of work.

27:17.102 --> 27:21.607 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Unemployment is just one of the
risk factors
that puts West Virginia right at
the heart

27:21.640 --> 27:23.842 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of the opioid epidemic.

27:23.876 --> 27:28.814 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's also a state with dangerous
jobs, not
just manufacturing, but coal
mining.

27:28.847 --> 27:29.948 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Workers get injured.

27:29.982 --> 27:33.385 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They are prescribed powerful
opioids for pain
relief.

27:33.418 --> 27:38.323 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That can begin a cycle of
addiction.

27:38.357 --> 27:43.028 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Jackson County Sheriff Tony
Boggs, who is
part of a community task force
to combat drug

27:43.061 --> 27:47.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
abuse, says heroin is now his
number one drug
problem, after marijuana.

27:47.933 --> 27:52.104 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TONY BOGGS, Jackson County
Sheriff: I think
in the mid- to late- '90s,
OxyContin was a

27:52.137 --> 27:53.438 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
huge ordeal.

27:53.472 --> 27:59.144 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
It was prescribed, in my
opinion, way out
of control.

27:59.177 --> 28:02.381 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It got a lot of people addicted.

28:02.414 --> 28:05.450 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Once it starts drying up, then
they have to
have something to turn to.

28:05.484 --> 28:09.855 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's whatever's easiest and
readily available,
and that has become heroin.

28:09.888 --> 28:13.892 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LISA STARK: This has not gone
unnoticed at
Cottageville Elementary.

28:13.926 --> 28:17.896 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TRACY LEMASTERS, Principal,
Cottageville Elementary:
We definitely see that impact.

28:17.930 --> 28:20.399 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
No one is waking them up to get
them to school.

28:20.432 --> 28:28.340 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They're often late because their
parents are
sleeping in because they had
partied too late

28:28.373 --> 28:29.341 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the night before.

28:29.374 --> 28:32.110 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
The child has no food.

28:32.144 --> 28:35.380 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They are hungry when they enter
the building.

28:35.414 --> 28:37.950 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They don't want to go home on
the weekends.

28:37.983 --> 28:43.455 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: Principal Tracy
LeMasters, who
holds a hallway huddle with her
staff every

28:43.488 --> 28:48.860 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
morning, regularly checks the
local paper
to see if any of her students'
parents have

28:48.894 --> 28:54.032 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
been arrested, so she and the
teachers can
be ready to help that child.

28:54.066 --> 28:56.101 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
TRACY LEMASTERS: It can be very
heartbreaking.

28:56.134 --> 29:02.241 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, I have -- I have
preschool students
that, freely, at mealtime, talk
about their

29:02.274 --> 29:04.042 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
mommies or daddies being in
jail.

29:04.076 --> 29:08.447 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: And under a new
program here,
called Handle With Care, law
enforcement now

29:08.480 --> 29:12.884 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
contacts the school districts if
they have
an interaction with a family
overnight.

29:12.918 --> 29:17.422 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TONY BOGGS: They will know that,
hey, that
kid had a rough night last
night.

29:17.456 --> 29:20.993 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's a reason that they're
acting out in
school today, or there's a
reason they are

29:21.026 --> 29:22.794 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
not here today.

29:22.828 --> 29:28.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA STARK: At Cottageville
Elementary, the
percentage of low-income
students is so high,

29:28.367 --> 29:34.973 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
